image.altText: Rishi Sunak stands in a blue suit speaking behind a lectern in the rain in the street

props.synopsis: Britain's Conservative Prime Minister Rishi Sunak calls a surprise general election, triggering a six-week campaign with his government trailing the opposition Labour Party in the polls.

title.children: British PM Rishi Sunak calls snap general election for July 4

image.altText: A composite image of three people.

props.synopsis: Britain's general election didn't have to be held for another six months, but Rishi Sunak's announcement to call a snap July poll might point to how desperate things have become inside his Conservative Party.

title.children: Why a crushing defeat might be as good as it gets for the UK's Conservatives

image.altText: Woman in a denim jacket and floral scarf speaks into microphone

props.synopsis: Uninjured Australians have begun their return to airports across the country, following "severe turbulence" that left 18 injured and one dead on Tuesday.

title.children: 'Hard to describe in words': First plane carrying Australians on turbulent Singapore Airlines flight touches down in Sydney

image.altText: Man looking in a mirror and smiling.

props.synopsis: Tully Denahy's diseased teeth were ruining his life. So, like thousands of Australians, he emptied his super account to pay for new ones.

title.children: 'Wasn't a difficult choice': Tully needed more than $50,000 to pay for his new teeth, so he drained his super balance

image.altText: A caravan park with cars and permanent shelters set up inside.

props.synopsis: Housing providers see more people forced into "filthy, unsafe, and overpriced" caravan parks on the New South Wales Central Coast as all other affordable options dry up.

title.children: Families living in caravan parks with 'dead kittens, mouldy furniture and violent neighbours' as housing crisis worsens

image.altText: Bailey Smith raises his eyebrows overlaid on a collage of red mullet silhouettes

props.synopsis: The ABC analyses the headshots and hairstyles of all AFL players in the 2024 season to definitively answer: is the mullet back?

title.children: The 'fashion forwards' cultural icon making a resurgence in Australian rules football

image.altText: A young lady looking worried

title.children: Family businesses struggling to pay ATO debts and desperate for cash fall victim to 'loan sharks'

image.altText: A LED light spelling the letter X is seen on top of an office building at night

props.synopsis: These "superspreaders" — including the official accounts of Donald Trump Jr and the Democratic party — prove difficult for social media giants to rein in.

title.children: 'Superspeaders' are responsible for most misinformation on Twitter — more than a third comes from just 10 people

image.altText: EV battery being removed

props.synopsis: More than half a billion dollars of federal government funds have been set aside to encourage production of batteries in Australia, but exactly how the scheme will work has not yet been figured out.

title.children: The national strategy to break China's stranglehold on the global battery supply chain

image.altText: Rikki Hoyland sits with her dog on her lap as she types.

props.synopsis: By the time she was 19, Rikki Hoyland had already been sexually assaulted twice. The Queensland youth worker represents a new generation of adolescents experiencing sexual assault at rates never seen before.

title.children: Sexual abuse rates are going down overall but among one group of people it's on the rise

image.altText: Peter Dutton sitting in the opposition leader's char in the house of representatives

props.synopsis: As we enter the final year of the parliamentary term, pressure is growing for alternative solutions. And if the Coalition's immigration policy announcement is anything to go by, it will need to lift its game on nuclear.

title.children: The detail of the Coalition's migration plan was delivered in fits and starts. It doesn't bode well for what's next

image.altText: A smiling woman holding her smiling son in a house with a white kitchen in the background

image.altText: A woman in a blue dress leans on a balustrade and looks out onto turquoise waters with corals.

props.synopsis: Tetepare was once home to tribes of people, before it was abruptly deserted about 200 years ago. Now, descendants are protecting it from logging and climate change.

title.children: Disease, headhunting and spirits are believed to have forced people from this island. Now, humans are back to protect it

image.altText: Geometric lines and shadows in entrance of building made of concrete and wood panelling.

props.synopsis: The nation's domestic spy agency says the threat facing Australia has changed since it was given the contentious powers in 2020.

title.children: ASIO says it no longer needs powers to question minors as young as 14

image.altText: Man with cap.

props.synopsis: The barrister for a woman whose husband died by poisoning has vehemently rejected rumour and innuendo that her client killed him.

title.children: Inquest into poisoning death of farmer Douglas Thrift hears wife had no motive to kill him

image.altText: Melbourne Airport

props.synopsis: A Victorian child has tested positive for H5N1 avian influenza after returning to the country from overseas earlier this year. The Department of Health says transmission to humans is rare.

title.children: First ever human case of bird flu detected in Victorian child returning to Australia

image.altText: A stylised image of a partially obscured man's face with scrabble-style tiles flying towards him

props.synopsis: James Raptis, the media lawyer identified by an ABC investigation as being linked to an AI plagiarism operation, has left his position at Australian Community Media.

title.children: Media lawyer resigns after ABC investigation reveals his links to plagiarism websites

image.altText: The side of a ship under construction with Spirit of Tasmanian in red text on a white background.

props.synopsis: The much-awaited two brand new Spirit of Tasmania ferries are due in the third quarter of this year, but with its Finnish shipbuilder in financial trouble and other problems of money and logistics, it has been anything but smooth sailing.

title.children: Delivery of first new Spirit of Tasmania in troubled waters after Finnish shipbuilder in need of government help

image.altText: Antony Blinken is seen out of focus as protesters behind him lift their hands with red-painted palms

image.altText: A young man wearing a cap sitting at a park table on a sunny day.

image.altText: Max Winchester and his wife Tiffany smile and pose together for a selfie in front of a pool.

image.altText: A bus crash seen from the air. The bus has crashed through trees

image.altText: A haunted house prop of a doll with long hair.

props.synopsis: Indonesia has one of the fastest-growing film markets in the world, and audiences can't get enough of one genre in particular.

title.children: Indonesia's film industry is on the rise and it's all thanks to the horror genre

image.altText: A close up of Greg Lynn standing in front of a body of water near some rocks.

props.synopsis: Police have revealed how they used data from number plate recognition cameras and a mobile phone to connect alleged Victorian High Country killer Greg Lynn to the disappearances of two campers.

title.children: Police used mobile phone data to link former pilot with missing Victorian campers, murder trial hears

image.altText: The interior of the Singapore Airlines plane

props.synopsis: As the world continues to burn fossil fuels, global temperatures are rising, and turbulence is just another natural phenomenon that's affected by that warming.

image.altText: Inside the Singapore Airlines flight

props.synopsis: While weather forecasts help pilots react, experts say the turbulence experienced on the Singapore flight was unexpected and rare.

image.altText: A woman with short hair looking off camera while standing next to a person

props.synopsis: South Australian doctors in general practices would be permanently exempted from paying payroll tax on earnings from bulk-billed services.

title.children: New payroll tax exemption will stop GP clinics from closing, peak medical body says

image.altText: Illuminated purple and white Telstra Shop signage outside Brisbane CBD store.

props.synopsis: Telstra's share price has fallen since CEO Vicki Brady made the announcement on Tuesday morning.

image.altText: A woman poses softly for the camera.

props.synopsis: Sven Lindemann used six knives to stab his girlfriend in front of her young daughter, angered that she wanted to leave the relationship.

image.altText: A woman in a white shirt smiles next to a door.

props.synopsis: Domestic violence comes at a great cost to victim-survivors, and it costs the nation billions. So, what can we do about it?

image.altText: Andrew Giles during QT

image.altText: A picture of a home with a for sale sign out the front.

image.altText: Mary Fowler holds up a Barbie doll in her likeness, wearing a soccer uniform, on her palm

image.altText: Matildas striker Sam Kerr

props.synopsis: The Australian striker was officially ruled out of the Games this week as she recovers from an ACL injury. So who will Tony Gustavsson turn to as the Olympics' 'group of death' draws nearer?

title.children: How will a Kerr-less Matildas tackle their 'group of death' at the Paris Olympics?
